{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":31404,"record_hash":"sha256:25b80123bcb4b697a59e622c172167e2f9a87e977aa783265a82324472ab6300","timestamp":"2026-05-11T17:34:25.271Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"That’s a valid hesitation.\n\nI’d separate the question into two parts:\n\n1. **Should GitMeta own scoped metadata mechanics?**  \n   I think yes. Scoped serialize/materialize/fetch refs are GitMeta semantics. If `but-agentlog` owns that, it will eventually reimplement GitMeta badly.\n\n2. **Should GitMeta’s main public API expose a one-shot `sync_scope()`?**  \n   This is less obvious. `sync_scope()` is a workflow opinion: fetch, serialize, materialize, serialize, push, retry. It may be useful, but it is also more “policy” than “primitive.”\n\nA nice compromise would be:\n\n- Keep `SyncScope` in `git-meta-lib`.\n- Keep scoped `serialize_scope()` and `materialize_scope()` in `git-meta-lib`.\n- Consider making the full `sync_scope()` orchestration less prominent:\n  - behind an `experimental`/`exchange` feature,\n  - in a separate module not re-exported at top level,\n  - or eventually in a small companion crate/CLI layer.\n\nFor the POC, having it in GitMeta helped prove the semantics. But before publishing, I’d be comfortable tightening the surface so the library exposes primitives first, and the “full sync loop” is treated as a convenience API rather than the core abstraction. That keeps GitMeta from accidentally blessing one lifecycle policy too early.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T17:34:25.271Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}